\par }{\b\f0\fs22\cf1\insrsid3347702\charrsid14289276 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 - The moment of exp\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 \hich\f0 losion\'85}{\f0\fs22\cf1\insrsid3347702\charrsid14289276 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
Let us assume that an atomic bomb explodes at an altitude of 2,000 m as it did in Hiroshima and Nagasaki. The neutrons bombarding the uranium and which split the first atoms into fragments creates chain reactions within the mass as mentioned befor
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e. In other words, the neutrons thrown out from the first fragmented nuclei hit other nuclei and split these new nuclei as well. Thus, all nuclei are rapidly fragmented in a chain reaction and the explosion occurs in a very short time. Neutrons move so fa
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t that the bomb releases a total energy of 1,000 billion kilo-calories during one millionth of a second. 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The temperature of the gas, into which the bomb is instantaneously converted, rises to several million degrees and the gas pressure rises to one milli\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 on atmospheres. 
\par }{\b\f0\fs22\cf1\insrsid15550680 
