\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  Just think: a human being, who is made up of the arrangement of atoms in various combinations, is born, is fed with atoms and grows up with atoms. He then reads books made of atoms in a bui\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
lding made of atoms. Later, he receives a diploma composed of atoms that says "nuclear engineer" on it. Yet, he can still come and deliver speeches such as "these atoms have come together as a result of sheer coincidence, and the extraordinary system with
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n them has formed by chance". If this is so, where does he derive the consciousness, will and intelligence to deliver this speech? 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 In almost every page of this book, we saw repeatedly that it is impossible for the atom making up every animate or inanimate\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 thing in the universe, to be itself formed by chance. What we will say to those who, despite all we have told, still think that this phenomenon has come about by "chance" or taken its present form through the mechanism of "trial and error" will be no dif
